Able	Soldier of Thom Tissy's 12th Squad, medium infantry, in the 9th Company of the 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Part of Adjunct Tavore Paran's punitive expedition against the Army of the Apocalypse, Able was counted among the more respectable veterans in the squad and was later pressed into sapper work during the march on Y'Ghatan.
Alardis	Commander attached to Admiral Nok's flagship staff as part of the forces assembled by Adjunct Tavore Paran. Assigned to take command of the Aren Guard garrison in place of Blistig, who was elevated to Fist and placed in charge of the 9th Legion.
Astabb	Nathii associate of the slavemaster Silgar, briefly seen among the searchers combing Silver Lake for Karsa Orlong after his escape. Astabb is only lightly sketched on the wiki, but appears as one of the uneasy retainers drawn into Silgar's pursuit of the Teblor through the bloodshed left behind in the town.
Aramala	Jaghut woman of the Jhag Odhan, tall and imposing, with pearlescent grey eyes and a long history of surviving the T'lan Imass. Hidden beneath a stone prison within a tower of Omtose Phellack, Aramala endured as one of the ancient presences still lingering in the odhan.
Bairoth Gild	Young warrior of the Uryd clan of the Teblor, age-contemporary of Karsa Orlong and Delum Thord. Heavier and shorter than his two companions, with a bear-like quality to his build. Rivalled Karsa for the affections of Dayliss and possessed a sharp wit, often deploying words with many-edged meanings that were lost on his rival. One of the three warriors who accompanied Karsa Orlong on the raid to Silver Lake.
Balantis	Fat, elderly Nathii merchant of Silver Lake with a wife, two children, servants, and a prosperous household. He appears as one of the townspeople caught up in the chaos unleashed when Karsa Orlong descends upon the settlement.
Balgrid	Squad mage in Borduke's 6th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Originally overweight, he grew into a thick-chested man described as solid as a tree trunk, with a bearded and appallingly unattractive face. An illusionist specialising in the Meanas warren, his skill at bending and cheating light in all directions impressed even fellow mage Bottle. He supplemented this with some facility in necromancy through Hood's Path and in healing through Denul.
Balm	Sergeant commanding the 9th Squad of medium infantry in the 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A tall, young, wide-shouldered Dal Honese with midnight skin, heavy eyebrows, jutting steering-oar ears, bulging yellowy eyes, and a face described as resembling a squashed gourd. Unusually, Balm was his real name rather than a soldier's nickname. Fiddler noted his cool indifference under pressure as an admirable quality. In the moments before battle, however, he was prone to a temporary disoriented state known as "the Confusion," in which he lost track of everything until fighting actually began. Held a low opinion of nobleborn officers and spoke badly accented Ehrlii.
Borduke	Sergeant commanding the 6th Squad in the 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Had a habit of pulling and tugging at his beard while deep in thought or under stress. Distrusted Captain Keneb, citing rumours that the captain had survived the Whirlwind by abandoning his men. Respected Fiddler's reputation as a former Bridgeburner and was willing to defer to his experience. Rumoured — though never proven — to have once thrown a nobleborn officer off a cliff near Karashimesh.
Bottle	Squad mage and marine in Sergeant Strings' 4th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A plain young man, thin as a spear and around twenty years of age; Fiddler noted the diffident bluster typical of young mages in him. His magical abilities derived primarily from witchery and spirit-lore taught to him by his grandmother, supplemented by access to the Warrens of Meanas, Thyr, and Hood's Path. His most distinctive talent was his ability to project his senses through the eyes and ears of animals and insects, making him an exceptional scout. Before enlisting — at the posthumous insistence of his grandmother's spirit — he had been selling charmed dolls to sailors in Jakatakan.
Borrug	Nathii in the employ of the slavemaster Silgar at Silver Lake, involved in the hunt for Karsa Orlong after the Teblor's escape from the slave trench. Borrug is presented as one of Silgar's hard-used retainers, following his master from the town into the misfortunes that followed the Malazan arrest.
Bowl	Huge, mean-looking heavy infantryman in the 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army, likely belonging to Sobelone's squad. Despite the general reputation of heavies for brawn over brains, Bowl showed an impressive aptitude for picking up new military specialties quickly.
Braven Tooth|Master Sergeant Braven Tooth	Grizzled master sergeant of the Malazan army based at the Malaz City garrison, infamous for training recruits through intimidation and for bestowing the nicknames many soldiers came to wear as their real names. A huge, filthy, black-haired veteran with a reputation stretching back decades, Braven Tooth loomed large in Malazan military lore and remained a formative presence for later Bonehunter soldiers.
Burnt	Corporal in Sergeant Moak's 11th Squad, medium infantry, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Part of Adjunct Tavore Paran's punitive expedition against the Army of the Apocalypse. His name was well known among soldiers of the legion alongside those of Moak and Stacker.
Calm	Female Forkrul Assail known among Teblor legend as a "Forkassal" and remembered as a Bringer of Peace. Imprisoned beneath a massive stone on the Laederon Plateau for ages untold, she was a figure of dread and worship to those who knew the old stories surrounding her prison.
Cynnigig	Ancient Jaghut of the Jhag Odhan, bent, gaunt, talkative, and proudly ignorant of the wider world's concerns. A survivor of old betrayals and a lover of horses, Cynnigig combined great age, evasive cunning, and comic verbosity in a way that made him one of the odhan's strangest lingering powers.
Corabb Bhilan Thenu'alas	Pardu officer in Leoman's company during the Whirlwind rebellion, famed for unwavering devotion, relentless battlefield luck, and a talent for surviving the most hopeless situations. Sixth son of a deposed chief and long a wanderer, Corabb fought with long-hafted axe-like weapons and carried scarab shells against evil, combining fanatic zeal with a strangely indestructible presence.
Cord|Sergeant Cord	Sergeant of the 5th Squad of the Ashok Regiment under Captain Kindly, later serving in the 9th Company of the 8th Legion within the Malaz 14th Army. A dark-skinned Seven Cities native with a scarred face, a tattoo-stitched bald pate, and a gleaming row of gold teeth, Cord was a seasoned infantryman who repeatedly held his squad together in brutal conditions and emerged as a dependable field leader among the former Ashok veterans.
Darist	Ancient Tiste Andii living on Drift Avalii, an immensely tall, black-skinned elder with white hair, amber eyes, and the distracted manner of a scholar carrying very old grief. He stood among the island's dwindling guardians of the Throne of Shadow and embodied the exhaustion and stubborn duty of that long watch.
Damisk	Nathii hunter and tracker who had once served in the Greydog army during the Malazan conquest and later became an associate of the slavemaster Silgar. Marked by a tribal tattoo on his brow, Damisk was one of the few lowlanders capable of surviving direct encounters with Karsa Orlong in the early House of Chains storyline.
Dayliss	Young woman of the Uryd clan of the Teblor, the object of rivalry between Karsa Orlong and Bairoth Gild for her affections.
Deadsmell	Corporal and squad mage in Sergeant Balm's 9th Squad of medium infantry in the 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A broad-chested man with a bearded chin and mostly hairless brows, his name was bestowed by Master Sergeant Braven Tooth. The squad's healer, he had access to High Denul. His necromantic abilities were rooted in skills acquired during his youth in the village of Gethran before his military service, drawing on Hood's Warren.
Delum Thord	Young warrior of the Uryd clan of the Teblor, age-contemporary of Karsa Orlong and Bairoth Gild. Quiet by nature and given to keeping his own counsel, contrasting with his more vocal companions. One of the three warriors who set out with Karsa on the raid to Silver Lake.
Duryl	Messenger in Sha'ik's Army of the Apocalypse, remembered as one of the functionaries caught up in Korbolo Dom's plotting on the eve of the Battle of Raraku. Though lightly sketched, Duryl belongs to the web of couriers, agents, and subordinates through whom the rebellion's internal betrayals were set in motion.
Ebron	Squad mage of Cord's 5th Squad in the Ashok Regiment, later continuing with the same core squad after it was absorbed into the Bonehunters. Born in Karakarang, Ebron wielded the warrens of Ruse and Rashan and was valued for dangerous, forceful battlefield sorcery, a dry wit, and the wary professionalism of a veteran mage who understood exactly how lethal his work could be.
Enias	Young Tiste Liosan warrior serving under Seneschal Jorrude, proud, pale, and eager to prove himself with the sword. Like his companions, Enias embodied the stern arrogance and martial certainty of the Liosan hunting their enemies through shattered warrens and into Seven Cities.
Ethume	Corporal in Sha'ik's Army of the Apocalypse, used by Korbolo Dom as one of the soldiers positioned for treachery on the eve of the Battle of Raraku. Ethume appears as part of the conspiracy's lethal machinery, one more subordinate drawn into Dom's violent attempt to seize control.
Fayelle	Sorceress in the Army of the Apocalypse and one of Kamist Reloe's lieutenants, described as obese, nervous, and dangerous. Once the instructor of Sinn, Fayelle stood among the Whirlwind's more ominous magical figures and was associated with dark personal history as well as Korbolo Dom's camp intrigues.
Flashwit	Heavy infantrywoman in Sergeant Mosel's squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A burly, round-faced Napan, she had shaved her head, wore a bronze nose-ring, and possessed arm muscles larger than Fiddler's thighs; the ground seemed to tremble when she walked. Her most striking feature was a pair of startlingly beautiful emerald green eyes, unusual enough that Gesler speculated her heritage extended beyond Napan. One of three soldiers known as the "dread ladies" of the heavy infantry alongside Mayfly and Uru Hela. She occasionally expressed a wish that she were smart enough to talk about things the way Bottle, Gesler, and Deadsmell did.
Galt	Pardu tribesman and medium infantryman in Sergeant Balm's 9th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Marked by facial tattoos and counted among the soldiers whose fighting was already known in the legion, Galt served as one of Balm's steadier squad members through the Seven Cities campaign and afterward.
Ganal	Warrior of the Sunyd clan of the Teblor of northern Genabackis. Held as one of Silgar's prisoners, Ganal is chiefly remembered for clashing verbally with Karsa Orlong even while both were trapped in the slaver's power.
Gentur	Kanese marine in Malazan service who survived the fighting on Drift Avalii with Traveller and other marines before eventually returning to Malaz City. A heavily armoured soldier armed with a crossbow, Gentur later became known as one of the castaways who frequented the Hanged Man Inn alongside Mudslinger.
Grub	Orphan boy adopted by Captain Keneb from among the survivors of the Chain of Dogs, raised in the company of the Malaz 14th Army. A toddler with a tangled shock of blond hair and a deeply tanned, cherubic face often smeared with dirt. Despite no formal mage training, unaccountably attuned to the mystical aspects of the world.
Gullstream	Crossbowman of the Ehrlitan Guard who later served as medium infantry in Thom Tissy's 12th Squad of the Bonehunters. Dark-skinned and striking enough that Smiles thought women noticed him twice, Gullstream was also known for a high blotched forehead and the habit of wiping his runny nose on his sleeve.
Greyfrog	Dog-sized demon companion of L'oric, reptilian in form, endlessly hungry, and possessed of a telepathic voice by turns grandiose, comic, and earnest. Though born of darkness and violence, Greyfrog often proved oddly loyal, unexpectedly tender, and far more companion than mere familiar.
Haran Epal	Logros T'lan Imass clansman in Ibra Gholan's company, one of the undead hunters pursuing the Unbound through the Nascent and into the struggle surrounding the First Throne. Though lightly sketched, Haran Epal stands among the stern ancient retainers of Logros duty.
Hawl	Old witch of Ruse, once a commander of the Talon and counted among the first of Kellanved's family. Presumed long dead after Laseen's purge, Hawl endured in secrecy as one of the hidden veterans of the old imperial order and was also remembered as Nok's wife.
Henaras	Sorceress in the Army of the Apocalypse serving under Korbolo Dom, alongside Fayelle as one of Kamist Reloe's lieutenants. Banished from her desert tribe and preserving a youthful appearance through magic, Henaras cultivated an air of languid menace and was trusted with potent wards and close protection.
Hubb	Corporal in Borduke's 6th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Part of Adjunct Tavore Paran's punitive expedition against the Army of the Apocalypse. Present at the 9th Company scorpion fight on the road to Raraku.
Ibb	Marine in Borduke's 6th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Part of Adjunct Tavore Paran's punitive expedition against the Army of the Apocalypse. Served as the vocal colour commentator during the inter-squad scorpion fights organised on the road to Raraku.
Imrahl	Ancient Khundryl warrior serving as aide to Gall of the Khundryl Burned Tears.
Ibra Gholan	Logros T'lan Imass clan leader who hunted the Unbound through the Nascent and later stood among the defenders of the First Throne. Clad in the skin of a dhenrabi and carrying the grave authority of his people, Ibra Gholan represented the stern command structure of the Logros clans.
Irriz|Captain Irriz	Renegade former corporal of the 3rd Company of the Ashok Regiment who joined the Whirlwind rebellion and promoted himself to captain. Wearing the trappings of a Malazan officer while leading a rebel force in Seven Cities, Irriz was especially driven by hatred for Captain Kindly and the Ashok veterans who had remained loyal.
Jibb	Former member of the Ehrlitan Guard who later became a medium infantryman in Thom Tissy's 12th Squad of the Bonehunters. He first appears as one of Karsa Orlong's guards in Ehrlitan and later stands among the soldiers drawn into Tavore's hard-marching campaigns.
Jorrude	Tiste Liosan seneschal and warrior-priest of Osric, a tall, pale, silver-haired commander whose sour severity and rigid sense of order made him emblematic of his people. He led a small band of Liosan through the shattered warrens in pursuit of trespassers and enemies, carrying the pride and grievance of Kurald Thyrllan with him.
Karsa Orlong|Karsa	Young warrior of the Uryd clan of the Teblor people, inhabiting the Laederon Plateau on the northern edge of Genabackis. Already into his eightieth year when he set out from his village, yet still considered a youngster by Teblor standards given their extended lifespan. A giant of a man, over seven feet tall and powerfully muscled. Driven by the desire to outdo the legendary raid of his grandfather Pahlk on Silver Lake, he set out with companions Bairoth Gild and Delum Thord to raid foreign territories and bring glory to the Uryd clan.
Kasanal	Assassin in the employ of Korbolo Dom and formerly a Semk shaman, noted for taking pleasure in killing and for preferring Malazan victims. Kasanal appears among the handpicked killers used in Dom's schemes within Sha'ik's camp, combining ritual background with a taste for violence.
Keeper|Ba'ienrok	Reclusive giant of Napan appearance living alone in a fossil-filled tower on the shore of the Otataral Sea. Calling himself Keeper and translating his local name Ba'ienrock for visitors, he was a formidable, secretive man with a paleontologist's obsession and a past he preferred buried.
Kindly|Captain Kindly	Captain in Malazan service who originally commanded the 2nd Company of the Ashok Regiment and later served with the Bonehunters. Renowned as one of the harshest and most intimidating officers in the Malazan military, Kindly was feared for his discipline, legendary caution, and savage tongue, yet also showed a hard-edged concern for the soldiers under his command. He was notably bald, obsessively proud of his collection of combs, and locked in a famously adversarial partnership with his lieutenant, Pores.
Koryk	Marine in Sergeant Strings' 4th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A large, half-Seti youth with a flat-featured face, broad shoulders, and long black hair that had a tendency to whip across his face. Conflicted over his mixed heritage, he decorated himself with Seti fetishes in homage to his roots yet chose to enlist in the marines rather than the cavalry as his Seti blood might otherwise have directed. Fiddler saw in him the mailed fist that every squad needed. Frequently came into conflict with his squadmate Smiles.
L'oric|High Mage L'oric	High Mage of the Apocalypse army, outwardly aloof and haughty, yet more thoughtful and reluctant than the warlike zealots around him. A tall figure in pale robes with access to Denul and deeper hidden powers besides, L'oric moved through the Whirlwind camp as one of its most mysterious and least straightforward servants.
Limp	Malazan soldier of Cord's 5th Squad in the 2nd Company of the Ashok Regiment, later continuing with the same core unit after its absorption into the Bonehunters. His nickname came from a training accident involving Braven Tooth and a fallen horse, and repeated leg injuries made the name stick with darkly comic inevitability.
Lobe	Medium infantryman in Sergeant Balm's 9th Squad of the 9th Company, 8th Legion, Malaz 14th Army. Not especially thoughtful by his own inclination but reliable with his weapons, Lobe was a familiar face among the Bonehunters and often appeared alongside Galt as one of the soldiers handling guard duty, shipboard fighting, and the rough daily business of the campaign.
Lutes	Squad healer in Borduke's 6th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A quiet, small man. Part of Adjunct Tavore Paran's punitive expedition against the Army of the Apocalypse.
Maybe	Marine sapper in Borduke's 6th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Originally from Aren, he had pale green eyes and was physically sickened in the presence of sorcery. Known within the company for his exceptional ability to retain facts. Before uniform standardisation, he wore a brass loop on one ear from which hung a human finger bone. Had a dry, satirical streak that Fiddler found irritating.
Mathok	Tall, fierce warleader of the desert tribes in the Army of the Apocalypse and a close ally of Leoman, widely regarded as beloved among the desert peoples despite a grating personality. A black-skinned, taciturn warrior with a weathered face and an air of innate nobility, Mathok embodied the martial authority of the tribal host gathered under Sha'ik.
Malachar	Tiste Liosan warrior in Jorrude's company, stern, pale, and armored in the ornate style of his people. Malachar carried the same harsh certainty and zeal for righteous violence that marked the Liosan band hunting enemies through the Nascent and beyond.
Monok Ochem	Logros T'lan Imass Bonecaster of massive frame and harsh judgment, famed for his hidden arts and his towering Soletaken ape form. Monok Ochem pursued the Unbound, distrusted weakness and deviation, and brought the grim authority of Tellann wherever he appeared.
Moak	Sergeant of the 11th Squad, medium infantry, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A copper-haired and bearded Falari, bearing a lance scar that ran the full length of his back from shoulders to tailbone. Renowned among his fellow soldiers for seeming to 'know things' — his hunches were passed along only to Tugg and Sobelone. His speculations included that Borduke had once thrown a nobleborn officer off a cliff near Karashimesh, and that Gesler had served as an under-age marine under Dassem Ultor, Cartheron Crust, or Urko Crust. Possessed an iron stomach — a rotten-fish stew he prepared on the road to Raraku left his entire squad ill while he himself suffered only belches.
Mosel	Sergeant of heavy infantry in the 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A lean man with epicanthic folds suggesting Kanese blood, wearing his hair braided and cut finger-length in the fashion of Jakatakan pirates — a typical mixed-heritage product of Malaz City. Protective of the soldiers under his command and quick to bristle at any perceived mockery directed at them. The youngest of the three heavy sergeants — alongside Sobelone and Tugg — who shared a threatening air that had less to do with size than attitude, and who resembled each other closely enough to pass for siblings.
Mudslinger	Malazan marine and Drift Avalii castaway, later serving as medium infantry in Thom Tissy's 12th Squad of the Bonehunters. Braven Tooth considered him a tough survivor, and his history on the edges of disaster fits that reputation.
Onrack T'emlava|Onrack|Onrack the Broken	Clanless Logros T'lan Imass once known as a Bonecaster, but more deeply defined by memory, art, and a restless sense of inward fracture. Bearing an obsidian blade and an ancient burden of failure and exile, Onrack became Trull Sengar's unlikely companion and one of the most reflective undead warriors in the House of Chains storyline.
Olar Shayn	Logros T'lan Imass clansman in Ibra Gholan's company, remembered for his rotted wolf fur, bone-hafted axe, and the bleak endurance typical of his people. Olar Shayn stood among the ancient hunters pursuing the Unbound through the Nascent and into greater conflicts of warrens and gods.
Orenas	Low-ranking Tiste Liosan warrior in Jorrude's band, pale and silver-haired like his companions but more often left with the practical duties of guard and retainer. Orenas helps give shape to the small, severe Liosan company stalking their foes through broken warrens and foreign lands.
Pahlk Orlong|Pahlk	Elder of the Uryd clan of the Teblor and grandfather of Karsa Orlong, venerated within the village as the last warrior to have led successful raids beyond Teblor lands. His tales of a youthful foray to Silver Lake were celebrated among the clan and served as the inspiration for his grandson's ambitions.
Phyrlis	Ancient Jaghut woman bound within the living body of a colossal tree on a hill in the Jhag Odhan, speaking softly by thought rather than by voice. Joined in strange symbiosis with the tree that preserved her, Phyrlis was an eerie yet nurturing presence tied to the survival of the odhan's Jhag horses.
Pores|Lieutenant Pores	Lieutenant Aramstos Pores, the long-suffering subordinate of Captain Kindly first in the Ashok Regiment and later among the Bonehunters. Sharp-witted and sardonic, he was one of the few soldiers able to match Kindly word for word, and their famously combative partnership became one of the Malazan army's enduring double acts.
Ramp	Medium infantryman of Thom Tissy's 12th Squad in the 9th Company of the 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Counted among the soldiers whose fighting on the march to Raraku had earned them broad recognition in the legion, Ramp later continued with the Bonehunters through some of their hardest campaigns.
Ranal	Young, noble-born Lieutenant commanding the 4th, 5th, and 6th Marine squads in the 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army, under Captain Keneb. A tall Quon man, fair-skinned and fair-haired, with high cheekbones, a wide straight nose, a full mouth, pale blue eyes, and a clean-shaven face. In front of his soldiers he adopted a grim officer's expression meant to project maturity, which Fiddler observed succeeded only in evoking the scowl of a constipated man. His inexperience in field conditions was apparent to the veterans under his nominal command.
Sands	Marine, sapper, and minor mage in Gesler's 5th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Part of Adjunct Tavore Paran's expedition against the Army of the Apocalypse. On the road from Aren to Raraku, helped Gesler inspect the squad scorpion fight entrants alongside Tavos Pond.
Scrawl	Member of the Ehrlitan Guard remembered for marking Karsa Orlong's face with the tattoo used to brand escaped prisoners. Though only briefly glimpsed, he is presented as a guard whose handiwork earned admiring comments from his fellow soldiers.
Scillara	Voluptuous camp follower in Sha'ik's army, known for a throaty laugh, sharp intelligence beneath an intoxicated facade, and a troubled past tied to the Ashok Regiment's abandoned camp followers. Raised amid exploitation in Raraku and long bound to Bidithal's influence, Scillara became a vivid presence among the wanderers and survivors moving through the Seven Cities storyline.
Shard|Corporal Shard	Corporal in Cord's squad, first in the Ashok Regiment and later in the Bonehunters. A young soldier and half-brother to Sinn, Shard was a hard, capable veteran whose blunt practicality and stubborn endurance carried him through some of the army's grimmest campaigns, even as he remained fiercely protective of his sister.
Shortnose	Heavy infantryman in the 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army, in either Sobelone's or Tugg's squad. Mean-looking, with huge hands and the tip of his nose cut off at some point in the past — the evident source of his name. Prone to extraordinarily loud snoring. Married fellow soldier Hanno during the march.
Sinn	Young mage of Malazan descent from Seven Cities and half-sister to Shard, later attached to the Bonehunters. Slight, pallid, and quietly unsettling even before her power fully emerged, Sinn was feared for the strange intensity of her talent and became one of the most formidable magical presences associated with the 14th Army.
Silgar|Slavemaster Silgar	Nathii slavemaster and priest of Mael based in Silver Lake, where he made his fortune trafficking Teblor of the Sunyd clan. Tall, thin, and severe-faced, Silgar stands as one of the earliest and most hateful lowlander antagonists encountered by Karsa Orlong.
Smiles	Marine in Sergeant Strings' 4th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Petite in build and disinclining to smile — the source of her pseudonym, assigned by Master Sergeant Braven Tooth. She preferred attacking from stealth and was skilled with the two thin-bladed knives she kept on her belt, serving as one of the squad's night scouts alongside Bottle. Fiddler noted the remorseless chill of her eyes reminded him of Sorry, and he found himself wondering whether there was murder in her past. Frequently came into conflict with her squadmate Koryk.
Sobelone	Sergeant of heavy infantry in the 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A severe-looking woman with streaks of grey in her shoulder-length black hair and eyes the colour of the sky. The oldest of the three heavy sergeants — alongside Mosel and Tugg — who together projected a threatening air that had less to do with size than attitude and who resembled each other closely enough to pass for siblings. Shared intelligence with Tugg through Sergeant Moak, who was reputed to 'know things'.
Squint	Veteran bowman of the Aren Guard and renowned marksman. Short and squat, with forearms muscled like hemp ropes, eyes like small black marbles nested in wrinkles, a bald head but for a fringe of long grey ratty strands, and a longbow as tall as himself. His uniform appeared not to have been washed or repaired in decades. He was later incorporated into Adjunct Tavore Paran's 14th Army.
Stacker	Corporal in Sergeant Moak's 11th Squad, medium infantry, in the 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. One of the soldiers whose name was already well known in the legion during Tavore's campaign across Seven Cities, Stacker was part of the tough core of veterans serving under Moak.
Synyg Orlong|Synyg	Son of Pahlk Orlong and father of Karsa Orlong, a warrior of the Uryd clan of the Teblor. Considered a disappointment to Pahlk for his reluctance to venture beyond the village and raid foreign territories. Owner of the prized destrier Havok.
Tarr	Corporal in Sergeant Strings' 4th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. A nondescript Hengan with pale, stolid features, placid pallid eyes, and a greying beard. Rather than carrying his oversized shield on his back like most soldiers, he kept it strapped to his left hand at all times, his equipment pack fitted with quick-release clasps so he could shed it with one hand while the other reached for his short thick-bladed sword. His scaled iron hauberk provided what he found a satisfying anchoring weight. He rarely spoke and was slow to act without orders — qualities Strings considered ideal in a corporal. His name derived from his time as a recruit, when Master Sergeant Braven Tooth spent nearly two bells attempting to dislodge him with a mace and could not move him once he had planted his feet behind his shield.
Tavos Pond	Meanas mage and marine in Gesler's 5th Squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army, later reassigned to Borduke's 6th Squad. A tall, dark, moustached man of probable Korelri origin.
Temul	Wickan warrior of the Foolish Dog clan, later identified as a member of the Crow clan. A scrawny, peach-faced fourteen-year-old lancer when first encountered among the Wickan horse warriors accompanying High Fist Coltaine's 7th Army. Participated in the Chain of Dogs, the grueling overland march across Seven Cities to the Malazan bastion at Aren. By the time of the 14th Army's campaign in Raraku, had adopted the full-body blue tattooing of the Crow clan, his face bearing an intricate geometric design resembling tesserae.
T'morol	Grizzled, burly bodyguard to Mathok in the Army of the Whirlwind, marked by cold hunter's eyes and the hard, weathered bearing of a desert veteran. Fiercely loyal to his warchief, T'morol appears as one of the blunt-edged tribal warriors who remained at Mathok's side through the rebellion's collapse.
Thom Tissy	Sergeant of the 12th Squad, medium infantry, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Virtually hairless, with a face that might be handsome to a female toad — cheeks heavily pocked, the backs of his hands covered in warts, dark beady eyes, calloused hands, and short bandy legs that left him as squat as an ogre. Wore a singular expression of disapproval as his default countenance. Despite his grim appearance, he was supportive and encouraging toward both his troops and superior officers.
Throatslitter	Hengese marine in Sergeant Balm's 9th Squad of medium infantry in the 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Pale-eyed, with scars on his neck and a habitually murderous expression. Carried twin long-knives in gloved hands. Possessed an uncanny shrieking laugh capable of silencing an entire tavern. Held a dim view of priests.
Traveller	Mysterious swordsman of extraordinary skill whose very presence unsettled gods and old soldiers alike. Seen among the survivors of Drift Avalii and marked by immense power, restraint, and old anger, Traveller moved through the margins of the story like a legend walking in plain sight.
Trull Sengar	Tiste Edur of House Sengar, second son of Tomad and Uruth, renowned for integrity, intellect, and a nearly compulsive truthfulness. Bald, scarred, and deadly with a spear, Trull stands apart for his modesty, self-awareness, and moral unease, making him one of the most reflective and quietly honorable figures to emerge from the Edur storyline.
Torvald Nom|Knuckles	Daru ne'er-do-well of House Nom, known to his Malazan enemies as "Knuckles." Tall, wiry, scarred, and resourceful, Torvald was an unwilling captive in Silver Lake who became Karsa Orlong's unlikely companion through imprisonment, shipwreck, and escape.
Tugg	Sergeant of heavy infantry in the 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army, hailing from Malaz City. The largest of the three heavy sergeants — alongside Mosel and Sobelone — with a thin, grating voice attributed to a damaged larynx. Carried a short single-bladed axe paired with an enormous hardwood shield sheathed in tin and rimmed in bronze, worn strapped to his back. He and his fellow heavy sergeants shared a threatening air that had less to do with size than attitude, and resembled each other closely enough to pass for siblings.
Uru Hela	Heavy infantrywoman in Sergeant Mosel's squad, 9th Company, 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Originally from Korel, she was surmised by Gesler to have been destined for service on the Stormwall before stowing away aboard a Jakatakan merchantman — a past he read as meaning she felt she owed nobody anything. One of three soldiers known as the "dread ladies" of the heavy infantry alongside Flashwit and Mayfly. Notable for a firm dislike of dishonesty.
Widdershins	Squad mage in Sergeant Balm's 9th Squad of medium infantry in the 8th Legion of the Malaz 14th Army. Described as an odd little man. Drew on the Warren of Meanas, the warren of illusions and deception.
